// echo.su — the smallest possible Sutra kernel service.
//
// Reads an axon on R_input, re-emits the same payload on R_output.
// In v0.0 this file is the seed source — services run as the Python
// stub `kernel.services.EchoService` because the kernel's .su loader
// (kernel.services.load_su_service) is staged for v0.1. The shape
// below documents what a real service .su looks like so the loader
// has a target convention.
//
// The convention this file commits to:
//   - The service exposes a function `on_axon(input_axon)` that
//     receives an inbound axon and returns the outbound axon (or a
//     vector if the caller will wrap it back into an axon).
//   - The kernel-side loader will call on_axon once per inbound
//     axon delivered to this process's inbox per tick.
//   - The function is pure: no side effects beyond returning the
//     output. Real-world side effects (timers, logging) flow through
//     additional axon channels, not through host-side hooks.

function vector on_axon(vector input_axon) {
    // For echo the body is trivial — read the inbound R_input slot,
    // return it on R_output. The router on the Python side is what
    // assigns roles to the wire; this function operates on raw
    // vectors so it stays substrate-pure.
    return input_axon;
}
